–1292","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1207–1285":"1207–1285","25 December 1223":"25 December 1223","1205":"1205","1223":"1223","1240 to 1241":"from 1240 to 1241","1264":"1264","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1292":"1292","about 1240":"about 1240","1207":"1207","Trabzon, Trabzon, Ottoman Empire":"Trabzon, Trabzon, Ottoman Empire","Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Cunynghame,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish:  see  Cunningham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cunningham","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the province of Cunningham in Ayrshire, first recorded in 1153 in the form <i>Cunegan</i>, a Celtic name of uncertain origin. The spellings in <i>-ham</i>, first recorded in 1180, and in <i>-ynghame</i>, first recorded in 1227, represent a gradual assimilation to the English placename element <i>-ingham</i>.","Irish: surname adopted from Gaelic <b>Ó Cuinneagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Cuinneagán</i>’, a personal name from a double diminutive of the Old Irish personal name <i>Conn</i> meaning ‘leader, chief’. This name is also adopted for <b>Ó Connacháin</b>, a variant of <b>Ó Connagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Connagán</i>’, from a diminutive of the personal name <i>Conn</i>.","History: A family of this name (see 1 above) can be traced back to Wernebald de Cunynghame, who was granted the manor of Cunningham by Hugh de Morville in the early 12th century."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Cunynghame, of Kilmaurs was born on 25 December 1223, in Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Hervius \" Hervy Henry                \" de Cunynghame, was 18 and his mother, Isabella Maud Riddell Heiress of Glengarnock, was 16. He married Margaret Dennieston from 1240 to 1241, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1285, in his hometown, at the age of 62."},"et":{"25 December 1223–1285":"25. detsember 1223–1285","1223–1285":"1223–1285","1240–1292":"1240–1292","1205–1264":"1205–1264","1207–1285":"1207–1285","25 December 1223":"25. detsember 1223","1205":"1205","1223":"1223","1240 to 1241":"1240 kuni 1241","1264":"1264","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1292":"1292","about 1240":"umbes 1240","1207":"1207","Trabzon, Trabzon, Ottoman Empire":"Trabzon, Trabzon, Osmanisches Reich","Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Kilmaurs, Ayrshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"25 December 1223–1285":"25. joulukuuta 122